# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1999-five-nations-championship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] The **1883 Home Nations Championship** was the inaugural series of the rugby union Home Nations Championship.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] Five matches were played between 16 December 1882 and 3 March 1883.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] It was contested by England, Ireland, Scotland, and Wales.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] England were the inaugural winners, and in beating the other three nations became the first winners of the Triple Crown although the phrase was not in use at the time (actually not before 1894).
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] The matches for this season were decided on goals scored.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] A goal was awarded for a successful conversion after a try, for a dropped goal or for a goal from mark.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] If a game was drawn, any unconverted tries were tallied to give a winner.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] If there was still no clear winner, the match was declared a draw.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] England started off their winning campaign by beating the newest of the home nations, Wales.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] This was the second meeting between the two countries and the first rugby union international hosted on Welsh soil.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] The match is also recognised as the first match where brothers of former international were also capped; England's Arthur Evanson and Arthur Taylor, brothers of Wyndham Evanson and Henry Taylor.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] Another first was referee A Herbert, the first Welshman to officiate an international rugby union match.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] After the humiliation of the first meeting between the two sides, when Wales lost by a margin of 13 tries, this game was seen as a vast improvement in play.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] The 'competent' Welsh team were undone by Australian Oxford scholar Gregory Wade, whose wing play the Welsh team had difficulty stopping.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] This was the very first time the home nations of Scotland and Wales had faced each other in a rugby union game.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] Wales lost this opening game, and it would take another six attempts for the Welsh to be victorious over the Scots.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] Wales turned up for the game one man short, so were forced to draft in Dr.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] Griffin of Edinburgh University as a replacement forward.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] The match also saw two Championship firsts; the first siblings to play in a Championship match AJ Walker and JG Walker, and also the first player to leave the field of play due to injury, when JG Walker twisted his knee in the first 15 minutes.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] This game also saw the last international match of the season for A.R.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] Don 'Bunny' Wauchope, when the talismanic Scot was incapacitated by a knee injury.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] Although the first meeting in the Championship between the countries, this was the ninth time Ireland and England had faced each other in an international rugby union game; and the ninth failure by the Irish to beat England.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] Wade was again the standout player for the English.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] However, Ireland played most of the game with 14 men, after R.W.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] Hughes withdrew after suffering terrible sea-sickness on the notoriously rough voyage across the Irish Sea.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] For Ireland four players were 'one cap' internationals, Fletcher, Warren, Forrest and Millar.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] The first meeting between the two countries in the Home Nations Championship was played on a heavily waterlogged pitch at North of Ireland's Ormeau Road.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] The Irish team suffered badly in the conditions and at one point were playing with just ten men due to injuries.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] Heavy Irish defending was the only reason the score line remained so close.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] Scotland continued their practice of capping promising schoolboys with the inclusion of Marshall Reid, an 18-year-old form Loretto School.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] With both England and Scotland victorious in their first two matches, this encounter became the Championship decider.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] England used six backs, to Scotland's five, and the tactic was successful with a narrow English win.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1883-home-nations-championship] The scoring of one of the English tries was greeted with derision by sections of the Edinburgh crowd, which was deplored by the President of the SRU at the after-game dinner.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] The **1884 Home Nations Championship** was the second series of the rugby union Home Nations Championship.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] Six matches were played between 5 January and 12 April 1884.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] England won the championship for the second consecutive season and in beating the other three nations won the Triple Crown for the second time.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] This Championship was most notable for a dispute arising from the game between England and Scotland, when the winning English try was disputed by the Scottish.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] The teams disagreed with the interpretation of a knock-on law from which England's Richard Kingsley scored and Scotland were told to accept the decision, and their request for adjudication was denied by England.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] The bitter feelings caused by this situation resulted in the creation of the International Rugby Board in 1886, to create an accepted body of rules that all members would agree to.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] This game was the first rugby union international game to be played in Yorkshire and the third game between the two countries.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] Although Wales lost the game by two tries, the result was a vast improvement on their prior two meetings, with Wales scoring their first try against England.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] The try came from English-born Charles Peter Allen, and was converted by Charles Lewis who was also the vice-president of the Welsh Rugby Union.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] The English play was dominated by Wade and Bolton, continuing their strong play from the previous Championship; Wade scored a try while Rotherham's score was set up after a 75-yard run from Bolton.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] The second meeting between the two teams resulted in another Scottish win.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] Both Scottish scores in this game were disputed by Wales, but this was a common occurrence.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] Welsh player William Gwynn took the ball over the line, but instead of touching down for a try he looked for support and was tackled.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] All three officials at the game were officials from three different rugby unions; the referee was James MacLaren, President of the RFU and the umpires were Richard Mullock, secretary of the WRU and JA Gardener, secretary of the SRU.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] When Ireland arrived in Wales for the 1884 encounter they were two players short.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] To allow the game to take place, uncapped substitute Welsh players were provided.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1884-home-nations-championship] Charles Jordan and Harry McDaniel, both of Newport RFC, took to the field as Ireland players, though contemporary reports continued to list the original chosen Irish players: Ernest Greene and Robert Gibson Warren.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1885-home-nations-championship] The **1885 Home Nations Championship** was the third series of the rugby union Home Nations Championship.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1885-home-nations-championship] It was contested by England, Ireland, Scotland, and Wales, but the tournament was not completed.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1885-home-nations-championship] The 1885 Championship was notable for the disputes occurring between the Home Nation Unions which prevented a full tournament to be completed.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1885-home-nations-championship] England and Scotland refused to face each other due to the refereeing disagreement from their 1884 encounter, and Wales and Ireland also failed to meet due to union disputes.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1885-home-nations-championship] The 1885 Championship also experienced a rare replay, when the Ireland versus Scotland game at Ormeau was abandoned after bad weather stopped play.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1886-home-nations-championship] The **1886 Home Nations Championship** was the fourth series of the rugby union Home Nations Championship.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1886-home-nations-championship] Five matches were played between 2 January and 13 March 1886.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1886-home-nations-championship] The 1886 Championship was shared by England and Scotland who both won two matches each.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1887-home-nations-championship] The **1887 Home Nations Championship** was the fifth series of the rugby union Home Nations Championship.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1887-home-nations-championship] Six matches were played between 8 January and 12 March.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1887-home-nations-championship] It was contested by England, Ireland, Scotland and Wales.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1887-home-nations-championship] Scotland won the championship outright for the first time, having shared the title with England in 1886; George Campbell Lindsay scored five tries against Wales, a record which still stands.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1888-home-nations-championship] The **1888 Home Nations Championship** was the sixth series of the rugby union Home Nations Championship.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1888-home-nations-championship] Three matches were played between 4 February and 10 March.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1888-home-nations-championship] It was contested by Ireland, Scotland and Wales.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1888-home-nations-championship] England were excluded from the Championship due to their refusal to join the International Rugby Football Board.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1888-home-nations-championship] Wales achieved their first victory over Scotland with a debut try from Pryce-Jenkins.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1888-home-nations-championship] After the try Wales switched their tactics to spoil the game by lying on the ball or kicking the ball into touch to prevent Scottish play.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1888-home-nations-championship] During the game Scotland grounded the ball over the Welsh line on five occasions but were not given a try by referee Chambers.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1888-home-nations-championship] This was Ireland's first win over Wales, which saw Ireland employ Shanahan, a forward, into a wing-forward role.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1888-home-nations-championship] This is believed to be the first time a forward had been used to fill a winging position.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1888-home-nations-championship] Shanahan had an excellent game, setting up Warren's try and scoring himself.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1888-home-nations-championship] Wales played poorly, with eight of the players, including captain Clapp, never selected to represent Wales again.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1888-home-nations-championship] This game was also noted as the first game in which the Welsh selectors made no changes in the Welsh pack keeping the same forward players as the match against Scotland.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1888-home-nations-championship] It was also the last time Wales fielded nine forwards, adopting the four threequarter system after its successful use in the encounter with the New Zealand Māori in December.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1888-home-nations-championship] The match was notable for being the last international game by Scotland's influential captain Charles Reid, who ended his career with twenty caps, a record for a forward.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1888-home-nations-championship] Although Ireland lost to Scotland for the sixth consecutive time, their superior score over Wales enabled them to win the tie-breaker decision for best record in the tournament, though the Championship itself was deemed not to have been completed due to the missing English side.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1889-home-nations-championship] The **1889 Home Nations Championship** was the seventh series of the rugby union Home Nations Championship.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1889-home-nations-championship] Three matches were played between 2 February and 2 March.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1889-home-nations-championship] England were excluded from the Championship due to their refusal to join the International Rugby Board.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1999-five-nations-championship] The **1999 Five Nations Championship** (sponsored by Lloyds TSB) was the 70th series of the rugby union Five Nations Championship.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1999-five-nations-championship] Including the previous incarnations as the Home Nations, this was the 105th series of the tournament.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1999-five-nations-championship] Ten matches were played over five weekends from 6 February to 11 April.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1999-five-nations-championship] The tournament was won by Scotland, who finished above England on points difference.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1999-five-nations-championship] It was notable for the dramatic climax to the tournament, which was decided in the dying minutes of the final match.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1999-five-nations-championship] England were heavy favourites to beat Wales and win the tournament and the grand slam.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1999-five-nations-championship] With England leading the match by six points as the clock passed 80 minutes, Wales centre Scott Gibbs evaded a number of tackles to score a try from approximately 20 metres.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1999-five-nations-championship] Neil Jenkins successfully converted to claim victory for Wales by a single point and hand the championship to Scotland in one of the most memorable matches in the tournament's history.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1999-five-nations-championship] Scotland had staged their own remarkable upset the previous day, scoring five first-half tries to beat France in Paris for only the second time in 30 years.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1999-five-nations-championship] Scotland's Gregor Townsend became only the fifth player in history to score a try against each other country in a single Five Nations tournament.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1999-five-nations-championship] He also became the second Scotsman to do so, following on from Johnnie Wallace in 1925.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1999-five-nations-championship] The others to achieve the feat were Carston Catcheside (England, 1924), Patrick Estève (France, 1983) and Phillipe Sella (France, 1986).
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1999-five-nations-championship] This was the last Five Nations Championship; in 2000, Italy joined the tournament, which became the Six Nations Championship.
[src:1999-five-nations-championship/1999-five-nations-championship] Italy played all of the Five Nations sides during the 1998–99 season, partly in preparation for joining the tournament the following year, albeit the game against England (at Huddersfield) was a World Cup qualifier.
